01:20.560 --> 01:23.029
I can't believe it.
Danny's bringing home a girl.

01:23.240 --> 01:24.390
I'm a nervous wreck.

01:24.600 --> 01:25.880
Mary, what are you
nervous about?

01:26.040 --> 01:29.192
Listen, a guy brings home a girl,
it's important. It's serious.

01:29.400 --> 01:32.757
I don't know. I used to
bring them home because
I couldn't pay for dinner.

01:33.840 --> 01:35.354
I hope she likes us.

01:35.560 --> 01:37.597
I hope she's nice.
Oh, God, I'm nervous.

01:37.800 --> 01:39.951
Mary, Mary, wait a minute.
You've got this all wrong.

01:40.160 --> 01:41.719
She's the one
being brought home.

01:41.920 --> 01:43.752
She's supposed to
be nervous, not you.

01:43.960 --> 01:45.553
You're right.

01:45.760 --> 01:48.673
I'm not being looked over.
I'm doing the looking over.

01:48.880 --> 01:50.872
Right.
I'm the one that has to like her.

01:51.080 --> 01:53.595
Right.
Then why am I so nervous?

01:54.040 --> 01:56.077
Mm! Beats me.

01:56.280 --> 01:59.478
Darling, there is one thing.

01:59.680 --> 02:02.718
This is obviously someone
Danny likes a lot.

02:02.920 --> 02:04.240
Someone special, you know?

02:04.440 --> 02:06.875
So I think we ought to get
to know her a little longer

02:07.080 --> 02:08.991
before we spring
certain things on her.

02:09.479 --> 02:11.038
Like what?

02:12.080 --> 02:15.198
Like if you get the urge
to become invisible, for example.

02:17.000 --> 02:18.957
I think that you ought
to get to know her

02:19.160 --> 02:21.231
before you let her
see you do that.

02:21.440 --> 02:23.238
Oh, well, yeah, of course.

02:23.440 --> 02:26.561
You know, I suppose I shouldn't
tell her about being committed
next week either.

02:26.680 --> 02:27.680
[DOORBELL RINGS]

02:27.880 --> 02:29.837
Oh, it's them. It's them.

02:33.000 --> 02:34.434
Hi.

02:37.440 --> 02:38.440
Mary.

02:38.600 --> 02:39.954
Burt, what are you doing?
Open the door.

02:40.160 --> 02:42.675
Mary, I hate to be the one
to tell you this.

02:42.880 --> 02:43.916
But it's a guy.

02:45.160 --> 02:46.160
What?

02:46.360 --> 02:49.512
It must be contagious.
Danny's as gay as Jodie.

02:49.880 --> 02:50.950
He's with a guy.

02:51.160 --> 02:53.040
Burt, what are you talking about?
Open the door.

02:53.240 --> 02:55.675
Okay, then you'll see.
Now, all right, Just don't scream.

02:56.880 --> 02:58.234
I'm in fruit city.

02:59.840 --> 03:01.718
Hey, you fruitcake,
get your hands off me.

03:01.920 --> 03:03.559
Burt, Burt, take it easy.

03:03.760 --> 03:05.160
He's a bodyguard.
What?

03:05.360 --> 03:07.397
Yeah, you see, Elaine's father,

03:07.600 --> 03:09.717
he worries about her,
so she has a bodyguard.

03:09.920 --> 03:13.038
And I thought
I was overprotective.

03:15.280 --> 03:18.432
Do we get to meet her
or does she just wave
from the car?

03:18.640 --> 03:21.109
No, no.
She'll be right in.

03:22.800 --> 03:24.837
Danny, have you
slept with her yet?

03:25.040 --> 03:26.269
[GROANS]

03:28.920 --> 03:32.516
I mean, because when you do,
what happens with the gorilla?

03:34.960 --> 03:36.997
Elaine, this is my mother,
Mary Campbell.

03:37.200 --> 03:38.350
Hello.
MARY: Hi.

03:38.560 --> 03:39.881
This is my stepdad,
Burt Campbell.

03:40.000 --> 03:41.878
Yes. Hello.
Mom, Dad.

03:42.080 --> 03:43.480
This is Elaine Lefkowitz.

03:43.680 --> 03:45.672
Jewish.

03:46.200 --> 03:47.200
What of it?

03:47.880 --> 03:49.633
Nothing. I love
Jewish people.

03:49.840 --> 03:53.117
Elaine, come in,
come in, sit down.

03:53.320 --> 03:55.073
Danny, Jewish?
So?

03:55.280 --> 03:56.401
You know about Jewish girls?

03:56.600 --> 03:58.239
What?
They're hot.

03:59.120 --> 04:02.591
You're gonna have yourself
a lot of fun here, if you aren't
already, I'll tell you.

04:02.800 --> 04:05.190
So come on, tell me,
how did you two meet?

04:05.960 --> 04:07.872
Well, he broke in
through my bedroom.

04:08.080 --> 04:09.514
[LAUGHING]

04:09.720 --> 04:12.189
Boy, you Jews got
the greatest sense of humour.

04:12.400 --> 04:13.400
It's the truth.

04:14.040 --> 04:15.920
You know, it's a good thing
you're here tonight,

04:15.960 --> 04:17.916
because next week
Burt's gonna be committed.

04:18.120 --> 04:20.315
He thinks he can
make himself invisible.

04:20.519 --> 04:24.116
I want you to know
everything about this family
before marrying into it.

04:25.400 --> 04:26.800
Hi, everybody.
Hey, hey, hey.

04:27.000 --> 04:28.719
[IN HIGH-PITCHED VOICE]
What is he, some kind of weirdo?

04:28.920 --> 04:29.876
[IN NORMAL VOICE] I don't know.

04:30.080 --> 04:31.992
Get your hands off me, you goon.

04:32.520 --> 04:34.352
See that? He thinks
that doll is real.

04:34.560 --> 04:37.359
And to tell you the truth,
sometimes, so do I.

04:37.560 --> 04:38.596
He's nuts.

04:38.800 --> 04:40.951
He's my son.
He's still nuts.

04:41.160 --> 04:42.389
Listen, miss.

04:42.600 --> 04:44.161
Hey, do I get to meet
the bimbo or what?

04:44.360 --> 04:45.874
Bob.

04:46.080 --> 04:49.312
Elaine, this is Chuck.
And Bob.

04:49.520 --> 04:50.874
Guys, this is Elaine Lefkowitz.

04:51.080 --> 04:52.080
CHUCK:
Hi.

04:52.240 --> 04:54.311
Hi. Nice coat.
Your folks polar bears?

04:57.800 --> 04:59.598
Throw her a fish,
maybe she'll do a trick.

04:59.800 --> 05:01.553
[BOB LAUGHING]

05:03.640 --> 05:04.915
Cute, huh?

05:06.040 --> 05:07.599
Hi.

05:08.320 --> 05:11.518
Danny, for me?
You shouldn't have.

05:14.920 --> 05:17.754
Hi. Don't you think
we should talk first?

05:21.120 --> 05:23.510
Is that Elaine?
That's her.

05:24.080 --> 05:27.312
Elaine, this is Jodie.
Jodie, this is Elaine Lefkowitz.

05:27.520 --> 05:29.352
Hi, Jodie.
Hi.

05:29.560 --> 05:31.392
Jodie's a fruit.

05:33.160 --> 05:35.755
Well, hey,
whose family's perfect?

05:35.960 --> 05:37.360
My father's a gangster.

05:39.920 --> 05:41.240
Your father's a gangster?

05:42.400 --> 05:44.073
Her father's a gangster.

05:44.280 --> 05:45.396
Hey, your son is a fruit.

05:45.600 --> 05:47.353
He's not my son.
He's my son.

05:47.560 --> 05:49.119
Well, he's crazy.

05:49.320 --> 05:52.154
All right. That's it.
I've had it. I'm leaving.

05:57.280 --> 05:59.317
Now he's invisible.

05:59.520 --> 06:01.751
Oh, my God. This is a zoo.

06:01.960 --> 06:05.920
So you wanna change your mind?

06:06.360 --> 06:08.716
Hey, cutie, wanna mess around?

06:10.080 --> 06:11.480
[LAUGHS]

06:11.680 --> 06:13.592
Excuse me.

06:13.800 --> 06:15.837
Can I have your attention,
please?

06:16.040 --> 06:20.717
I am sure Danny called
and told you all to act
as strange as possible.

06:20.920 --> 06:22.593
Well, I'm afraid
you've oversold it.

06:23.160 --> 06:25.391
No family can be this crazy.

06:25.600 --> 06:28.035
So like it or not,
Danny's little trick didn't work,

06:28.240 --> 06:31.039
and we're gonna go ahead
with our plans.

06:31.240 --> 06:34.312
What plans?
Well, you see, Ma, it's...

06:34.520 --> 06:35.590
[CLEARS THROAT]

06:35.800 --> 06:40.079
Danny and I are getting married.

06:42.040 --> 06:43.156
Oh, wonderful.

06:43.360 --> 06:45.920
He'll get a blood test
and the bear'll get a rabies shot.

06:47.360 --> 06:49.317
[♪♪♪]

07:07.400 --> 07:08.550
I don't know, Father.

07:08.760 --> 07:11.116
I just don't think
this retreat is working.

07:11.320 --> 07:13.118
I mean, I still think about her.

07:13.320 --> 07:17.473
In fact, I think I think about her
more here than I did back home.

07:17.680 --> 07:21.230
But that could be because
I need something to keep
my mind off this cold.

07:21.440 --> 07:23.750
Listen, I know we're not
supposed to ask for signs.

07:23.960 --> 07:25.599
We're supposed to go on faith.

07:25.800 --> 07:28.440
But do you think you can
give me a sign anyway?

07:28.640 --> 07:31.792
I mean, just something to let me
know I'm on the right track.

07:33.200 --> 07:34.680
Tim?

07:38.440 --> 07:40.716
My God. Is this the sign?

07:40.920 --> 07:42.798
Tim.

07:45.880 --> 07:47.109
Corinne.

07:47.320 --> 07:49.755
Corinne, how did you
get here? No one can
get here.

07:49.960 --> 07:51.679
The place is totally isolated.

07:51.880 --> 07:54.031
It wasn't easy, let me tell you.

07:54.240 --> 07:56.596
I had to hire an Indian guide
to help me up the mountain,

07:56.800 --> 07:58.120
and halfway up, he quit.

07:58.320 --> 08:00.312
It's below zero out there.

08:00.520 --> 08:02.352
It's below zero in here.

08:02.560 --> 08:04.074
Tim, is this where you live?

08:04.640 --> 08:07.633
Yes. Corinne,
you can't stay here.

08:07.840 --> 08:09.718
You can't stay here either.
It's freezing.

08:09.920 --> 08:12.674
Now, there's a beautiful hotel
down the mountain in Banff.

08:12.880 --> 08:13.880
You'll love it.

08:14.040 --> 08:16.600
There's fireplaces
and room service.

08:16.800 --> 08:18.757
Let's go, Tim.

08:19.200 --> 08:22.796
Corinne, I came here
for a reason, remember?

08:23.000 --> 08:24.957
To forget you.
Have you?

08:26.960 --> 08:28.189
No.

08:28.400 --> 08:30.198
Good.

08:30.880 --> 08:32.360
Father Tim...

08:32.559 --> 08:35.234
Ohh. It's a vision.

08:35.440 --> 08:37.591
Father Tim, a vision. Ooh!

08:42.880 --> 08:43.950
Corinne, get out of here.

08:44.159 --> 08:47.471
In one minute, that guy's gonna
be on the phone with Rome,
and they'll declare a new saint.

08:47.680 --> 08:49.592
Now go.
Go?

08:49.800 --> 08:52.190
After what I went through
to get up here?

08:52.400 --> 08:54.198
You think it was easy?

08:54.400 --> 08:56.995
I mean, I buy a new outfit,

08:57.200 --> 08:59.840
and I travel to another country,

09:00.040 --> 09:02.077
and then with my history
of dizzy spells,

09:02.280 --> 09:06.797
I climb a mountain with
an Indian who has not seen
a woman in three years.

09:07.840 --> 09:09.957
And I finally get here
and you say "Go"?

09:10.600 --> 09:13.479
Forget it. You've got
yourself a roommate.

09:16.520 --> 09:18.159
Listen, Corinne.

09:18.360 --> 09:20.591
I came up here to get over you.

09:20.800 --> 09:22.154
But it's not working.

09:22.360 --> 09:25.637
But I have to see it through.
I have to finish it.

09:25.840 --> 09:28.594
So please, go,
and I'll see when I'm done.

09:28.800 --> 09:30.632
It's not working?

09:31.560 --> 09:32.960
No.

09:34.720 --> 09:36.313
She smiles.

09:36.520 --> 09:39.831
I'm a priest probably in love
with a woman, and she smiles.

09:40.440 --> 09:42.352
In love?

09:42.560 --> 09:45.200
Corinne, please, go.

09:46.120 --> 09:47.793
Okay.

09:48.000 --> 09:50.356
No. No, the way
you came.

09:50.560 --> 09:51.835
Okay.

09:53.160 --> 09:54.594
Hurry.

09:58.920 --> 10:01.719
But I'll be down at that hotel.

10:04.840 --> 10:06.513
She was here. She was.

10:06.720 --> 10:08.791
It was a vision, right,
Father Tim?

10:09.000 --> 10:10.559
She was a vision, all right.

10:11.360 --> 10:13.033
But she's gone now.

10:13.920 --> 10:16.719
The Lord giveth.
The Lord taketh away.

10:17.520 --> 10:21.400
Yeah. Maybe I've been
on the mountain too long.

10:21.760 --> 10:23.717
[♪♪♪]

10:28.160 --> 10:30.117
[♪♪♪]

10:35.240 --> 10:37.391
Well, I've never been so
embarrassed in all my life.

10:37.600 --> 10:39.796
Why?
To have to call Sheriff Tinkler

10:40.000 --> 10:41.673
to report your father's
disappearance

10:41.880 --> 10:44.839
the very morning that you're
to go on trial for murder?

10:45.040 --> 10:47.635
It's insane what's happening
to this family.

10:47.840 --> 10:52.278
I know. We certainly are
having our run of bad luck.

10:52.920 --> 10:54.479
As if all that
wasn't bad enough,

10:54.680 --> 10:57.195
the new tie that I was going
to wear this morning?

10:57.400 --> 10:58.400
It's missing.

10:58.600 --> 11:00.881
Well, you should have told
Sheriff Tinkler about that too.

11:00.960 --> 11:03.919
And while he's looking for Daddy,
he could look for your tie.

11:04.880 --> 11:06.712
Jessica.

11:07.640 --> 11:10.401
Well, I've checked around
and none of the neighbours
have seen Grandpa.

11:10.520 --> 11:12.079
Some say they hope
they never do.

11:12.280 --> 11:15.273
And three say if they
see him, they'll kill him.

11:15.800 --> 11:19.680
Jessica, when your father
left last night, did he say
where he was going?

11:19.880 --> 11:22.475
Oh, Chester. You know it doesn't
matter where he says he's going.

11:22.680 --> 11:25.240
You remember the last time
he said he was going for a walk

11:25.440 --> 11:28.353
and he overpowered the driver
of that Löwenbräu beer truck

11:28.560 --> 11:30.711
and claimed it for America?

11:32.760 --> 11:35.434
Well, maybe Benson
knows where he is.

11:35.640 --> 11:36.790
Where's Benson?

11:37.000 --> 11:38.320
Mother, is that what
you're wearing to court?

11:38.520 --> 11:39.520
Well, yes.

11:39.680 --> 11:41.194
Well, I don't know
about that dress.

11:41.400 --> 11:44.960
I mean, I think what you
wanna do is wear a colour that's
the most sympathetic to the jury.

11:45.120 --> 11:46.713
Jessica, where's Benson?

11:46.920 --> 11:49.640
Black should do it. I mean,
widows wear black to funerals

11:49.840 --> 11:52.196
and look how much sympathy
they get.

11:52.720 --> 11:54.791
No, I think black
is too depressing.

11:55.000 --> 11:57.310
Eunice. Jessica. Benson.

11:57.520 --> 11:58.556
What about Benson, dear?

11:58.760 --> 12:00.479
Where is he?
I don't know, Chester.

12:00.680 --> 12:04.117
Perhaps he's with Daddy
and your new tie.

12:06.720 --> 12:08.837
Benson, where's the major?

12:09.040 --> 12:11.475
How am I supposed to know?

12:12.200 --> 12:15.671
You look wonderful, Benson.
Thank you.

12:16.320 --> 12:19.916
Benson, you know
the major gets in trouble.
You're supposed to watch him.

12:20.120 --> 12:23.352
Ah, ah, ah. It ain't my job
to watch him.

12:23.560 --> 12:26.792
Now, the only thing I got to
watch around here is what's
cooking in my oven.

12:27.000 --> 12:28.229
You want me to watch him,

12:28.440 --> 12:31.592
you put him on a platter with
a lot of little potatoes around.

12:33.240 --> 12:35.709
You know, Jessica,
it's a good thing I'm not a bigot,

12:35.920 --> 12:38.560
because if I were,
I could say a few things right here.

12:38.760 --> 12:39.989
Like what?

12:41.200 --> 12:44.272
Beige. You should wear beige.
Beige is the perfect colour, Mother.

12:44.480 --> 12:46.915
Benson, I think
I tied this wrong.

12:47.120 --> 12:48.713
That's my tie.

12:48.920 --> 12:50.721
That's right. See, I don't
have one of my own.

12:50.840 --> 12:53.309
So I asked Benson to pick one
of yours that would be suitable.

12:53.520 --> 12:55.671
You gave him my new tie?

12:55.880 --> 12:57.394
How about that?

12:58.680 --> 13:01.149
He can't wear that.
I'm wearing that.

13:01.360 --> 13:03.511
It's all yours.

13:05.160 --> 13:07.675
Major, where have you been?

13:07.880 --> 13:08.880
Hi, Gramps.

13:09.040 --> 13:10.793
Daddy, where have you been?

13:11.960 --> 13:13.553
Chester, he's not answering.

13:13.760 --> 13:15.433
I can see that, Jessica.

13:15.640 --> 13:19.600
But he is smiling,
so wherever he's been,
it was nice.

13:20.200 --> 13:22.840
I think I am in love.

13:23.040 --> 13:25.430
Chester, Daddy's got a girlfriend.

13:25.640 --> 13:27.040
Ugh.

13:28.560 --> 13:30.233
Where did you meet her, Daddy?

13:30.440 --> 13:32.432
I met her in the cemetery.

13:32.640 --> 13:34.279
I go to see my old friends there.

13:34.480 --> 13:38.474
I have lots of friends there,
and there she was.

13:38.680 --> 13:41.036
Sheeba Fifer.

13:41.240 --> 13:44.039
That's her name,
and I'm in love with her.

13:44.240 --> 13:47.119
Sheeba Fifer.

13:47.320 --> 13:49.630
Sheeba Fifer.

13:49.840 --> 13:52.799
I don't think I know the family.

13:53.400 --> 13:54.880
Where did you spend the night?

13:55.520 --> 13:58.115
Colonel, as an officer
and a gentleman,

13:58.320 --> 14:00.516
you shouldn't even ask
that question.

14:01.400 --> 14:04.393
This is the real thing.
This is it.

14:04.600 --> 14:09.516
I haven't felt like this
since my dear, departed,
beloved wife.

14:09.720 --> 14:12.394
Whoever she was.

14:12.600 --> 14:14.557
[♪♪♪]

14:15.320 --> 14:17.277
Benson.
BENSON: What do you want?

14:17.480 --> 14:20.200
I need you up here.

14:21.320 --> 14:23.710
Jessica, come on out of there.

14:24.200 --> 14:25.634
Jessica, this is a murder trial.

14:25.840 --> 14:27.797
It's not a party
where it's chic to be late.

14:28.000 --> 14:29.601
JESSICA: I'm not going.
What do you mean?

14:29.720 --> 14:31.552
I'm not going.
You're not going at all?

14:31.760 --> 14:33.080
I'm not going at all.
I see.

14:33.280 --> 14:35.590
You know they'll put you
in jail for this, Jessica.

14:35.800 --> 14:38.952
Jessica, I'm not going to
let you do this to yourself.

14:39.160 --> 14:41.072
Well, I'll have to
break down the door.

14:41.280 --> 14:45.069
Stand back, Jess, because
the wood is going to fly.

14:48.200 --> 14:50.396
Nice work, Clint.

14:54.440 --> 14:58.559
Good, solid door. They don't
make doors like this anymore.

14:58.760 --> 15:00.240
When are we going?

15:00.440 --> 15:02.636
As soon as I get your mother
out of the bathroom.

15:02.840 --> 15:05.833
Benson, I want you to go
downstairs, get a ladder, go up...

15:06.040 --> 15:07.997
Go up on the roof
and through the window.

15:08.200 --> 15:10.078
Is he talking to me?

15:10.680 --> 15:11.955
What, are you crazy?

15:12.160 --> 15:14.038
I ain't going up on no roof.

15:14.240 --> 15:16.436
You go up on the roof.
I'll do it.

15:16.640 --> 15:18.393
No, you won't.
BILLY: Oh, come on.

15:18.600 --> 15:21.479
Last time you were up
on the roof, you spent
the summer in traction.

15:21.680 --> 15:23.399
I ain't going up on the roof
and neither are you.

15:23.600 --> 15:24.920
We've gotta get her
out of there, Benson.

15:25.120 --> 15:26.236
So you go up there.

15:26.440 --> 15:28.830
Well, Benson, don't you think
I would if I could?

15:29.040 --> 15:30.474
No.

15:31.560 --> 15:34.314
Well, I can't. I get nosebleeds.

15:34.520 --> 15:35.590
Nosebleeds?

15:35.800 --> 15:38.190
I'll give you nosebleeds.

15:38.680 --> 15:40.592
All right, all right. I'll do it.

15:40.800 --> 15:43.395
JESSICA:
No, Benson. I don't want
you climbing on that roof.

15:43.600 --> 15:44.600
It's dangerous.

15:44.760 --> 15:48.197
Well, I'm gonna have to
go up on the roof if you
don't get out of there.

15:48.400 --> 15:51.393
So if I go up there
and break my neck,
it'll be on your head.

15:54.920 --> 15:56.513
Thank you.

15:59.360 --> 16:00.396
Don't be afraid, Jess.

16:00.600 --> 16:02.990
You won't be found guilty.
Mallu is the best.

16:03.200 --> 16:04.600
Oh, I know that, Chester.

16:04.800 --> 16:07.759
And I'm not really afraid of that.

16:07.960 --> 16:09.110
What are you afraid of?

16:09.320 --> 16:11.357
Well, I can't tell you.
You'd think I'm crazy.

16:11.560 --> 16:13.438
No, I won't.

16:13.640 --> 16:16.155
I'm afraid for the trial
to be over.

16:16.360 --> 16:18.113
What, are you crazy...?

16:19.400 --> 16:20.516
Why, Jess?

16:20.720 --> 16:22.837
Because it's brought us
close together.

16:23.040 --> 16:25.919
We're close now, Chester.
We talk, we laugh, we drink wine.

16:26.120 --> 16:29.238
We spend our evenings together
and our weekends together.

16:29.440 --> 16:31.636
It's been just like
a honeymoon, Chester.

16:31.840 --> 16:33.641
Well, that's the way
it usually happens, Jess.

16:33.720 --> 16:35.800
It generally takes a crisis
to bring people together.

16:35.840 --> 16:38.355
But it's just been so wonderful,
I don't want it to end.

16:38.560 --> 16:41.280
And I'm afraid that when
the trial's over it will.

16:41.480 --> 16:42.834
But why?

16:43.040 --> 16:46.272
Well, you know,
if I'm found innocent,

16:46.480 --> 16:48.312
then the crisis will be over.

16:48.520 --> 16:50.716
And we'll just go back
to being strangers.

16:50.920 --> 16:53.276
And if I'm found guilty,
it'll definitely be over,

16:53.480 --> 16:55.790
because I'll be on death row.

16:56.560 --> 16:59.075
That won't happen, Jess.
I won't let it. I promise.

16:59.280 --> 17:00.839
Really, Chester?
Really, Jess.

17:01.040 --> 17:02.040
JESSICA:
Oh!

17:02.200 --> 17:04.156
[♪♪♪]

17:06.240 --> 17:08.196
[CHATTERING]

17:10.040 --> 17:13.875
Hello, I'm Carol David,
Mr. Mallu's assistant.
And you are?

17:14.079 --> 17:16.595
Mary Campbell.
This is my husband, Burt.

17:16.800 --> 17:18.233
Thank you.

17:18.440 --> 17:19.510
And you?

17:19.720 --> 17:23.316
Danny.
Right. And, uh...?

17:23.520 --> 17:24.714
Chuck.
Chuck.

17:24.920 --> 17:25.876
[IN HIGH-PITCHED VOICE]
And Bob.

17:26.079 --> 17:27.355
[MOUTHS] <i>That's Bob.</i>

17:29.560 --> 17:30.880
And you're Jodie?

17:31.080 --> 17:32.230
You sound surprised.

17:32.440 --> 17:34.079
You're the suicidal homosexual?

17:34.280 --> 17:36.112
Do we have mutual friends?

17:36.920 --> 17:39.230
Well, no, no, it just says,
I mean...

17:39.440 --> 17:42.911
Well, what did you expect,
that I'd be in a dress with
a noose around my neck?

17:43.120 --> 17:45.191
[JODIE & DANNY LAUGHING]

17:48.800 --> 17:54.910
I'm sorry. I guess what threw me
is you're just so adorable.

18:00.680 --> 18:03.036
Most suicidal homosexuals are.

18:04.480 --> 18:07.439
Listen, when court
adjourns for lunch,

18:07.640 --> 18:10.200
give me a chance to start off
on a better foot?

18:12.000 --> 18:14.640
[WHISPERS] Go on, go on, go on.

18:15.960 --> 18:17.235
Please.

18:18.360 --> 18:19.476
Okay.

18:25.440 --> 18:27.671
Hear ye. Hear ye.
The court is now in session,

18:27.880 --> 18:30.236
with the honourable
Anthony "Presillo pretriding."

18:30.440 --> 18:32.272
Petrillo presiding.

18:36.040 --> 18:38.191
The court will please rise.

18:43.920 --> 18:45.400
All right, everyone be seated.

18:51.440 --> 18:53.511
Where the hell is she?
This is a murder trial.

18:53.720 --> 18:55.677
You can't be late
for your own murder trial.

18:55.880 --> 18:58.031
Counsellor,
where's the defendant?

18:58.240 --> 18:59.674
Your Honour, they were detained.

18:59.880 --> 19:01.553
I think she should be here
any second.

19:01.760 --> 19:05.754
Something must have happened,
Your Honour, because Jessica's
always on time.

19:05.960 --> 19:08.794
That's one thing about Jessie.
She's never, ever late.

19:09.000 --> 19:11.151
Counsellor, who's that?

19:11.360 --> 19:13.875
Her sister, Your Honour,
Mary Campbell.

19:14.080 --> 19:17.437
And this is my husband, Burt.
And these are my sons.

19:17.640 --> 19:19.711
That's Burt's son.

19:20.400 --> 19:24.155
You know, last night,
Jessie had a little upset stomach.

19:24.360 --> 19:26.158
Maybe she was feeling
a little nauseous.

19:26.360 --> 19:27.874
Sit down.

19:30.000 --> 19:33.960
Hello, hello, hello.

19:35.880 --> 19:39.157
I'm sorry.
I'm sorry I kept you waiting.

19:39.360 --> 19:40.919
I'm sorry, Your Honour.

19:41.120 --> 19:43.760
But we simply could not find
a parking spot outside.

19:43.960 --> 19:46.794
I thought surely there would
be one reserved for the defendant.

19:47.000 --> 19:48.036
But there wasn't.

19:48.240 --> 19:51.153
Everything was marked
"Official parking only."

19:51.360 --> 19:53.920
And Chester said,
"This is just another example

19:54.120 --> 19:58.080
of the idiotic inefficiency
of the judicial system."

20:02.480 --> 20:05.314
Is this my jury?

20:05.520 --> 20:07.557
Oh, hello.
Mrs. Tate.

20:07.760 --> 20:09.638
Hello.
Mrs. Tate.

20:11.080 --> 20:14.357
Will you please sit down?

20:14.560 --> 20:15.914
Nice outfit.

20:16.480 --> 20:17.480
What's this for?

20:17.680 --> 20:20.070
In case you want to
jot something down
or write me a note.

20:20.280 --> 20:21.720
Why would I want to
write you a note?

20:21.880 --> 20:24.440
I'm sitting right next to you.

20:25.080 --> 20:29.597
Oh, I'm sorry, if I go
to Europe in the spring,
I'll write you a note.

20:30.200 --> 20:32.396
Counsellor, are you ready?

20:32.600 --> 20:34.831
Yes, Your Honour.
Is it all right if I doodle?

20:35.040 --> 20:36.759
Yes. Yes.

20:39.440 --> 20:42.194
Oh, look who's here.

20:42.400 --> 20:45.234
Hello, hello, Mr. Franklin.

20:45.440 --> 20:47.318
Mrs. Tate, do you realise...?

20:47.520 --> 20:49.796
Judge, judge, judge,
hold that thought one minute.

20:50.000 --> 20:52.071
We'll get right back to you.

20:54.120 --> 20:57.113
Don't you think it's silly
for all of us to sit at two
big tables?

20:57.320 --> 21:00.677
I mean, it creates an almost
antagonistic atmosphere.

21:00.880 --> 21:03.793
Sort of them versus us.

21:04.000 --> 21:07.835
Don't you think it would
be better if we all sat
at one large table?

21:08.040 --> 21:09.997
Much warmer and
friendlier that way.

21:10.200 --> 21:12.078
Mrs. Tate. Mrs. Tate.

21:12.280 --> 21:15.159
I've endured your stalling
tactics long enough.

21:15.360 --> 21:17.352
Counsellor, please.

21:20.120 --> 21:23.591
All right, Mr. Franklin.
You can begin your
opening statement.

21:23.800 --> 21:25.393
Thank you, Your Honour.

21:26.920 --> 21:28.798
Ladies and gentlemen
of the jury,

21:29.000 --> 21:31.913
we have here an unusual case.

21:32.120 --> 21:35.796
Unusual in the sense that,
this being a small town,

21:36.000 --> 21:38.640
the defendant is familiar
to most of you.

21:38.840 --> 21:40.479
You must, however,

21:40.680 --> 21:44.594
I repeat, you must divorce yourself
from any previous opinions

21:44.800 --> 21:46.871
you may have of the defendant,

21:47.080 --> 21:52.200
and instead pay attention
only to what you hear in this room.

21:52.400 --> 21:55.438
And what you will
hear in this room,
ladies and gentlemen,

21:55.640 --> 22:00.795
is, I'm afraid, a chilling story
of how a wife and mother

22:01.360 --> 22:05.115
cold-bloodedly, methodically,
and with malice aforethought,

22:05.320 --> 22:06.470
committed murder.

22:06.680 --> 22:09.957
Oh! A mother?

22:14.160 --> 22:15.560
How awful.

22:17.640 --> 22:19.359
Yes, ladies and gentlemen,
it is true.

22:19.560 --> 22:22.553
And I will show you
how Jessica Tate,

22:22.760 --> 22:25.753
an angry, spurned,
frustrated woman...

22:25.960 --> 22:27.440
What?

22:27.640 --> 22:31.395
With hate in her heart,
in cold blood,

22:31.600 --> 22:33.193
murdered Peter Campbell.

22:33.400 --> 22:37.030
Oh, please, Mr. Franklin.

22:41.600 --> 22:45.719
I have never heard anything
so rude and awful in all my life.

22:45.920 --> 22:48.071
Now, Mrs. Tate,
one more word from you

22:48.280 --> 22:50.158
and I'm gonna hold you
in contempt.

22:50.360 --> 22:51.430
Me?

22:51.640 --> 22:54.678
Well, if there's any
contempt around here,
it's coming from him.

22:54.880 --> 22:58.157
I have never heard anything
so contemptible in all my life.

22:58.360 --> 23:00.750
And I am not going
to stand for it.

23:00.960 --> 23:02.713
I'm going.

23:05.920 --> 23:07.559
[CHATTERING]

23:08.600 --> 23:09.750
All right.

23:09.960 --> 23:11.519
All right, all right, I'll stay.

23:11.720 --> 23:12.870
But I must warn you,

23:13.080 --> 23:16.835
if you continue in this manner,
I will not come back tomorrow.

23:18.720 --> 23:21.110
Go on now, but be nice.

23:24.320 --> 23:27.836
The prosecution
will attempt to show,
ladies and gentlemen...

23:29.720 --> 23:31.677
ANNOUNCER:
<i>Will Danny marry Elaine?</i>

23:31.880 --> 23:35.920
<i>Or will he choose the carefree life</i>
<i>of a bachelor and have his head</i>
<i>blown off?</i>

23:36.120 --> 23:39.113
<i>Will Father Tim leave</i>
<i>the retreat to see Corinne?</i>

23:39.320 --> 23:42.597
<i>And if he does, will they</i>
<i>make him pay for the window?</i>

23:42.800 --> 23:47.317
<i>Will Jessica be found guilty</i>
<i>of the heinous crime that</i>
<i>Franklin has accused her of?</i>

23:47.520 --> 23:49.637
<i>And what does heinous mean?</i>

23:49.840 --> 23:52.150
<i>These questions and many others</i>
<i>will be answered</i>

23:52.360 --> 23:54.829
<i>on next week's episode of</i> Soap.

23:55.040 --> 23:56.997
[♪♪♪]

